Here's a pragmatic version. Full RFC 5322 compliance is a nightmare (the official regex is absurd), so this covers the realistic cases you actually want to accept/reject:

```javascript
function isValidEmail(s) {
  if (typeof s !== "string") return false;

  // One @, non-empty local part, domain with a dot and a 2+ char TLD.
  // No leading/trailing dots, no consecutive dots.
  const re = /^[A-Za-z0-9._%+-]+@[A-Za-z0-9.-]+\.[A-Za-z]{2,}$/;
  if (!re.test(s)) return false;

  const [local, domain] = s.split("@");
  if (local.length > 64 || s.length > 254) return false;
  if (/\.\./.test(s)) return false;                 // no consecutive dots
  if (/^\.|\.$/.test(local) || /^\.|\.$/.test(domain)) return false;

  return true;
}
```

Notes:
- The regex is the gate; the follow-up checks catch the things a single regex handles badly (length limits per RFC 5321, consecutive dots, edge-position dots).
- This rejects some technically-valid-but-exotic addresses (quoted local parts like `"a b"@x.com`, IP-literal domains like `user@[127.0.0.1]`). That's almost always what you want for a signup form.
- For correctness-critical flows, the only real validation is sending a confirmation email. Regex tells you it's plausibly an address, not that it exists.

