Here's a pragmatic implementation. Truly RFC-5322-complete validation is overkill for almost every use case (and the real answer for deliverability is "send a confirmation email"), so this covers the practical cases without false-rejecting normal addresses.

```javascript
function isValidEmail(s) {
  if (typeof s !== "string") return false;

  // One @, non-empty local + domain, no whitespace, domain has a dot,
  // and no leading/trailing/double dots in either part.
  const re = /^[^\s@]+(\.[^\s@]+)*@[^\s@]+(\.[^\s@]+)+$/;

  return s.length <= 254 && re.test(s);
}
```

Notes:
- `length <= 254` is the practical max for an email address.
- The pattern forbids spaces, requires exactly one `@`, and requires at least one dot in the domain with no empty labels (rejects `a@b`, `a@b.`, `a@.b`, `a..b@c.com`).
- It does *not* handle exotic-but-legal forms (quoted local parts like `"a b"@x.com`, IP-literal domains like `user@[10.0.0.1]`). If you need those, you're better off with a vetted library (`validator.isEmail`) than a hand-rolled regex.

