Here's a pragmatic implementation. Email validation is genuinely hard to do perfectly (the full RFC 5322 grammar is enormous), so the right move is a sensible practical regex plus a few structural guards that catch the common invalid cases.

```javascript
function isValidEmail(s) {
  if (typeof s !== "string") return false;

  // One @, non-empty local + domain, no whitespace, domain has a dot-separated TLD.
  const re = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
  if (!re.test(s)) return false;

  // Structural guards the regex above doesn't enforce.
  const [local, domain] = s.split("@");
  if (local.length > 64 || domain.length > 255) return false;       // RFC length limits
  if (s.length > 254) return false;                                  // total length limit
  if (local.startsWith(".") || local.endsWith(".")) return false;   // no leading/trailing dot
  if (local.includes("..") || domain.includes("..")) return false;  // no consecutive dots
  if (domain.startsWith("-") || domain.endsWith("-")) return false;  // domain edges

  return true;
}
```

Notes:
- `[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+` is the workhorse: exactly one `@`, something before it, and a domain with at least one dot. It rejects `a@b` (no TLD), `a @b.com` (space), `a@@b.com`, and empty parts.
- The guards add the structural rules a single regex reads poorly for (length caps, dot placement).
- It accepts quoted-string locals and IP-literal domains as invalid — that's intentional. Those are valid per RFC 5322 but vanishingly rare and usually not what you want to allow.

⚠ The only way to *truly* know an address is valid is to send mail to it. For form validation, this is the right level of strictness. If you need a battle-tested library instead, `validator.js` (`isEmail`) is the usual pick.

