  // No whitespace, no consecutive dots, no leading/trailing dots in either part.
  const re = /^[^\s@.]+(?:\.[^\s@.]+)*@[^\s@.]+(?:\.[^\s@.]+)+$/;

  return email.length <= 254 && re.test(email);
}
```

What it accepts/rejects:
- ✓ `a@b.co`, `first.last@sub.domain.com`, `user+tag@gmail.com` (the `+` is in the local-part char class via `[^\s@.]`)
- ✗ `a@b` (no TLD), `a..b@c.com` (double dot), `@b.com`, `a@.com`, `a b@c.com`
- The 254 char cap is the practical RFC limit on a full address.

Caveats worth knowing:
- This rejects quoted local parts (`"john doe"@x.com`) and IP-literal domains (`a@[127.0.0.1]`). Both are technically valid per RFC 5322 but virtually never appear in real input, so most validators skip them on purpose.
- No regex proves an address is *deliverable*. If you need that certainty, the only real validation is sending a confirmation email. Treat this as a syntax gate, not a guarantee.

