```js
function isValidEmail(s) {
  if (typeof s !== "string") return false;

  const email = s.trim();
  if (email.length === 0 || email.length > 254) return false;

  // One @, splitting local and domain parts.
  const at = email.lastIndexOf("@");
  if (at <= 0 || at === email.length - 1) return false;

  const local = email.slice(0, at);
  const domain = email.slice(at + 1);

  if (local.length > 64) return false;

  const localOk = /^[A-Za-z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+(\.[A-Za-z0-9!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+)*$/.test(local);

  const domainOk =
    /^(?=.{1,253}$)([A-Za-z0-9](?:[A-Za-z0-9-]{0,61}[A-Za-z0-9])?)(\.[A-Za-z0-9](?:[A-Za-z0-9-]{0,61}[A-Za-z0-9])?)+$/.test(domain);

  return localOk && domainOk;
}
```

What it enforces:
- Exactly one effective `@`, with non-empty local and domain.
- Length limits (254 total, 64 local, 253 domain) per the relevant RFCs.
- Local part: standard unquoted atom chars, no leading/trailing/double dots.
- Domain: dot-separated labels, each 1–63 chars, alphanumeric with internal hyphens, requires at least one dot (so `user@localhost` fails — drop the `+` to a `*` if you want to allow bare hostnames).

What it intentionally skips: quoted local parts (`"a b"@x.com`), IP-literal domains (`user@[192.168.0.1]`), and IDN/unicode (run it through `URL`/punycode first if you need those). If you want, I can give you a stricter or looser variant.

